Generic MongoDB Logging for ROS
===============================


For the conceptual background please refer to the paper "A Generic
Robot Database and its Application in Fault Analysis and Performance
Evaluation" by Niemueller et al. [1].
For technical information please refer to the project's website [2].
The ROS wiki page gives more details on how to get started on ROS [3].

[1] http://www.fawkesrobotics.org/publications/2012/robodb-iros2012/
[2] http://www.fawkesrobotics.org/projects/mongodb-log/
[3] http://www.ros.org/wiki/mongodb_log




0. get server ip (system 1) with:
ip address 
ping ip from other (system 2) to confirm that they are on the same network
1. open file named postgresql.conf:
this to locate 
sudo find / -name postgresql.conf
or
sudo updatedb
locate postgresql.conf
sudo nano postgresql.conf # sudo nano /etc/postgresql/12/main/postgresql.conf
2. add this line to that file:
listen_addresses = '*'
3. then open file named pg_hba.conf:
locate pg_hba.conf
sudo nano pg_hba.conf
4. and add this line to that file:
host  all  all 0.0.0.0/0 md5
5. Also, This line:
local   all             postgres            peer
Should be:
local   all             postgres            md5
It allows access to all databases for all users with an encrypted password
6. restart postgres

sudo systemctl restart postgresql

7. test the connection on (system 2)

psql -h 192.168.1.115 -U postgres
password: root

postgres=# \q --â†’ exit


################################################################

Step 1: Install PostgreSQL
You can install PostgreSQL 12 using the command
sudo apt install postgresql
Step 2: Set root user credentials
Login to PostgreSQL shell using the command
sudo -u postgres psql
Then set root user credentials using the command
ALTER USER postgres PASSWORD 'root';
# sudo -u postgres psql -c "ALTER USER postgres PASSWORD 'root';"
sudo passwd postgres
		root
Step 4: Install pgAdmin (recommended)
pgAdmin is the most popular and feature rich Open Source administration tool for PostgreSQL. Create the repository configuration file:
curl https://www.pgadmin.org/static/packages_pgadmin_org.pub | sudo apt-key add

sudo sh -c 'echo "deb https://ftp.postgresql.org/pub/pgadmin/pgadmin4/apt/$(lsb_release -cs) pgadmin4 main" > /etc/apt/sources.list.d/pgadmin4.list && apt update'
pgAdmin4: to install complete mode, use the command:
sudo apt install pgadmin4
After saving changes restart PostgreSQL server:
sudo /etc/init.d/postgresql restart

